SIMPLE: rectify
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rectify
<hw>Rec"ti*fy</hw> <pr>(-f?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Rectified</conjf> <pr>(-f?d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Rectifying</conjf> <pr>(-f?`?ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[F. <ets>rectifier</ets>, LL. <ets>rectificare</ets>; L.
<ets>rectus</ets> right + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See
<er>Right</er>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make or set
right; to correct from a wrong, erroneous, or false state; to amend;
<as>as, to <ex>rectify</ex> errors, mistakes, or abuses; to
<ex>rectify</ex> the will, the judgment, opinions; to <ex>rectify</ex>
disorders.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I meant to <qex>rectify</qex> my conscience.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This was an error of opinion which a conflicting opinion would
have <qex>rectified</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To refine or purify by repeated
distillation or sublimation, by which the fine parts of a substance are
separated from the grosser; <as>as, to <ex>rectify</ex> spirit of
wine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>To produce ( as factitious gin or
brandy) by redistilling low wines or ardent spirits (whisky, rum, etc.),
flavoring substances, etc., being added.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- (Elec.) To convert (alternating current) to direct current.
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To rectify a globe</b></col>, <cd>to adjust it in order
to prepare for the solution of a proposed problem.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To amend; emend; correct; better; mend; reform;
redress; adjust; regulate; improve. See <er>Amend</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rectilinear</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Rectilineal</ent>⟦br⟧
